Rolpe Dorje
\f1\b0 \'a0({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_Tibetan_language"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Standard Tibetan}}:\'a0
\f2 \uc0\u3938 \u3964 \u3939 \u3851 \u3924 \u3936 \u3954 \u3851 \u3938 \u4001 \u3964 \u3851 \u3938 \u3991 \u3962 \u3851 \u3962 \u3851 
\f1 ) (1340\'961383) was the fourth\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gyalwa_Karmapa"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Gyalwa Karmapa}}\'a0(the head of the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karma_Kagyu"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Karma Kagyu}}, a subschool of the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kagyu"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Kagyu}}\'a0School of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tibetan_Buddhism"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Tibetan Buddhism}}). According to legend, the fourth Karmapa's mother, while pregnant, could hear the sound of the mantra\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Om_Mani_Padme_Hum"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Om Mani Padme Hum}}\'a0while the child was in her womb and the baby said the mantra as soon as he was born. His early life was full of miracles and manifested a total continuity of the teachings and qualities of his former incarnation, including receiving teachings in his dreams. While in his teens, he received the formal transmissions of both the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kagyu"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Kagyu}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nyingma"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Nyingma}}\'a0lineages from the great Nyingma guru Yungt\'f6npa, the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rangjung_Dorje"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 third Karmapa}}'s spiritual heir, now very advanced in years. At the age of nineteen, he accepted\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toghon_Tem%C3%BCr"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Toghon Tem\'fcr}}'s invitation to return to China where he gave teachings for three years and established many temples and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gompa"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 monasteries}}.\
On his return to\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tibet"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Tibet}}, while in the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tsongkha"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Tsongkha region}}, Rolpi Dorje gave lay ordination to a very special child, whom he predicted to be of great importance to Buddhism in Tibet. This was\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Je_Tsongkhapa"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Tsong Khapa}}, the future founder of the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gelugpa"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Gelugpa}}\'a0school, famous for its\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dalai_Lama"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Dalai Lamas}}.\
When Temur died, the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuan_dynasty"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Mongol dynasty}}\'a0of China ended and the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ming_dynasty"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Ming dynasty}}\'a0began. The new emperor invited Rolpi Dorje, who declined the invitation but sent another\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lama"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 lama}}\'a0in his stead. Rolpi Dorje composed mystic songs throughout his life and was an accomplished poet, fond of Indian poetics. He is also remembered for creating a huge painting ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thangka"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3\i \cf4 \strokec4 thangka}}) following a vision of one of his students, who had imagined a\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddhist_art"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Buddha image}}\'a0over a 100 metres tall. The Karmapa, on horseback, traced the Buddha's outline with hoofprints. The design was measured and traced on cloth. It took 500 workers more than a year to complete the thangka, which depicted the\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gautama_Buddha"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Buddha}},\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maitreya"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Maitreya}}\'a0and\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manjusri"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Manjusri}}; the founders of\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahayana"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \strokec4 Mahayana}}.\
